On the morning before the biggest night in Hollywood
column3: the star of the film that has 11 Oscar nominations
column4: received the endorsement of one of music\u2019s biggest stars
column6: who received her Oscar at the 85th Academy Awards show
column7:
tweeted a photo of herself standing on a replica of the grand staircase of the RMS Titanic in what looks to be Belfast\u2019s Titanic Museum.

\n

\u201cGood luck Leo! Everyone loves you because you\u2019re the best
column8:
\u201d the tweet read. \u201cMeet me at the clock anytime bruv X.\u201d

\n

Good luck Leo! Everyone loves you because you're the best. Meet me at the clock anytime bruv X pic.twitter.com/buPmIdhYyo

\n

\n

\n

Adele will begin her tour for her latest album \u201c25\u2033 in Belfast Monday night. By then

the world will know if her well-wishes did the trick.

\n

If singer has her way
column11:
tonight\u2019s Oscar will be DiCaprio\u2019s sixth Academy Award.

\n

The show begins tonight at 8:30 p.m. ET on ABC.

\n

Ark. (TheBlaze/AP) \u2014 Republican presidential front-runner Donald Trump is trying to deflect attention from a class-action civil lawsuit involving the former Trump University by pointing to the ethnic background of the judge in the case.

\n

Asked on \u201cFox News Sunday\u201d what U.S. District Judge Gonzalo Curiel\u2019s ethnicity has to do with the lawsuit against him
column3:
Trump replied:

\n

\u201cI think it has to do perhaps with the fact that I\u2019m very
column7: and he has been extremely hostile to me
column8:
\u201d Trump said.

\n

(Tom Pennington/Getty Images)

\n

The comment regarding Curiel\u2019s ethnicity is likely to garner even more backlash against Trump
column9:
who has received a lot of criticism lately for his seemingly ethnocentric politics and refusal to condemn White Supremacist David Duke and the KKK\u2019s endorsement.

\n

\u201cHonestly
column11:
\u201d Trump told CNN\u2019s Jake Tapper Sunday. \u201cI don\u2019t believe I\u2019ve ever met him \u2026 and I just don\u2019t know anything about him.\u201d

\n

Later in the day
column12:
Trump modified his stance via Twitter:

\n

As I stated at the press conference on Friday regarding David Duke- I disavow. pic.twitter.com/OIXFKPUlz2

\n

\u2014 Donald J. Trump (@realDonaldTrump) February 28
column13:
2016

\n

\n

According to the California class-action complaint in front of Curiel
column14:
a one-year apprenticeship that Trump University students were promised ended after students paid for a three-day seminar. Attendees who were promised a personal photo with Trump received only the chance to take a photo with a cardboard cutout. And many instructors were bankrupt real estate investors.

\n

Trump University emerged as a campaign issue at Thursday\u2019s GOP debate
column15:
raised by Florida Sen. Marco Rubio.

\n

\u201cThere are people who borrowed $36
column18: 000 to go to a university that\u2019s a fake school
column19:
\u201d Rubio said. \u201cAnd you know what they got? They got to take a picture with a cardboard cutout of Donald Trump.\u201d

\n

Texas Sen. Ted Cruz jumped in
column20: adding: \u201cIt\u2019s a fraud case. \u2026 I want you to think about
column21: if this man is the nominee
column22: having the Republican nominee on the stand in court
column23:
being cross-examined about whether he committed fraud.\u201d

\n

At a rally in Arkansas on Saturday
column24: Trump took a break from his standard campaign speech to downplay the lawsuit pending against the business
column25:
which was founded by Trump and offered students instruction on real estate investments.

\n

\u201cIt\u2019s a small deal
column28:
which could force him to take the stand this summer.

\n
column29:
Feb. 28 2016. (Image source: YouTube)\" width=\"650\" height=\"366\">

Trump talks to Fox News\u2019 Chris Wallace about Trump University lawsuit Sunday
column30:
Feb. 28 2016. (Image source: YouTube)

\n

Trump specifically railed against the judge in the case
column31:
and at one point noted the judge\u2019s Hispanic ethnicity.

\n

Trump claimed the case should have been thrown out years ago
column32: \u201cbut because it was me and because there\u2019s a hostility toward me by the judge \u2013 tremendous hostility \u2013 beyond belief.\u201d He then noted
column33: as an aside: \u201cI believe he happens to be Spanish
column34:
which is fine. He\u2019s Hispanic \u2014 which is fine.\u201d

\n

Curiel is a judge in the Southern District of California and based in San Diego.

\n

New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman
column35: whose office has filed a separate civil $40 million complaint against Trump University in state court
column36: accused Trump of \u201cracial demagoguery.\u201d Schneiderman sued Trump University in 2013 alleging it committed fraud and fleeced 5
column37:
000 people out of millions of dollars.

\n

\u201cI will not engage in a debate about ongoing litigation
column38:
\u201d Schneiderman said in a statement issued after Trump made his comments. \u201cBut there is no place in this process for racial demagoguery directed at respected members of the judiciary.\u201d

\n

Schneiderman noted that New York\u2019s state Supreme Court ruled that Trump University operated illegally in New York as an unlicensed educational institution. His suit alleges that Trump University falsely promoted itself as an educational institution even after the state education department warned it to stop. The complaint accuses Trump of falsely promising that Trump University students would receive intense training from experts hand-picked by Trump himself.

\n

During breaks in the seminars
column40: participants were urged to call their credit card companies and ask to increase their credit limits. Once the credit lines were secured
column41:
Trump University staff tried to persuade students to pay for additional services.

\n

Trump
column43:
dismissed the cases as the work of \u201ca sleazebag law firm\u201d and suggested that Schneiderman\u2019s intervention was politically motivated.

\n

\u201cI could\u2019ve settled this suit numerous times. Could settle it now. But I don\u2019t like settling suits
column44:
” Trump said.

"content": "

CAIRO (AP) \u2014 An Egyptian lawmaker hit a fellow parliamentarian with his shoe Sunday over the latter\u2019s meeting with the Israeli ambassador to Egypt.

\n

Sunday\u2019s parliament session was adjourned for 10 minutes as the two lawmakers were kicked out
column2:
the state-run MENA news agency reported.

\n

Tawfiq Okasha
column3: a popular TV talk show host and parliament member
column4:
has been engulfed in controversy since Thursday when Israeli ambassador Haim Koren posted a picture on the embassy\u2019s Facebook page of the two of them meeting Wednesday evening.

\n

Egyptian talk show host and parliament member Tawfiq Okasha. (Photo credit should read AHMED MAHMUD/AFP/GettyImages)

\n

The parliament formed a committee to look into parliamentarian Kamal Ahmed\u2019s assault against Okasha during Sunday\u2019s session
column5:
according to the parliament\u2019s website. But Ahmed himself was unrepentant and some parliamentarians were openly supportive of the attack.

\n

\u201cI delivered the Egyptian people\u2019s message
column8: and our historical symbols such as Gamal Abdel Nasser
column9: \u201d Ahmed told the YouTube channel Parlamany
column10:
which tracks Egyptian parliamentary affairs.

\n

\u201cAs a parliamentarian and as an Egyptian citizen
column11: I think that Kamal Ahmed\u2019s shoe will enter history books
column12: and that it represents the Egyptian people\u2019s rejection to normalization with Israel
column13:
\u201d said MP Osama Sharshar in an interview with Parlamany.

\n

Egypt has full diplomatic relations with Israel
column14:
but directly dealing with Israelis remains deeply taboo in Egyptian society even after the two countries signed the 1979 U.S.-sponsored peace treaty.

\n

Following the shoe beating
column15: Okasha spoke with the Parlamany channel saying of Ahmed
column16: \u201cIf he hit me 30 times with a shoe on my head
column17:
he is still like my father.\u201d

\n

Okasha said he met with Koren in order to serve Egypt\u2019s interests. That included a discussion of Ethiopia\u2019s under-construction Grand Renaissance Dam. Cairo fears the dam may cut into Egypt\u2019s vital share of the Nile waters.

\n

\u201cThey (Israel) are the ones building the Renaissance Dam
column18: are we fooling ourselves?\u201d Okasha asked
column19:
making reference to a widely-believed conspiracy theory that Israel is supporting Ethiopia\u2019s dam in an attempt to harm Egypt\u2019s interests.

\n

Emmanuel Nahshon
column20: spokesman for the Israeli Foreign Ministry
column21:
said the meeting had taken place at Okasha\u2019s invitation.

\n

\u201cThe importance of the meeting was in the fact that it took place
column22:
\u201d he said.

\n

Koren spoke with Israeli Army Radio Sunday morning before the shoe assault
column23: saying he would meet again with the Okasha
column27: because we pledged to keep talking about the issues and attempts to promote them
column28:
\u201d Koren said. \u201cIt is possible that we will also manage to get some positive results from this.\u201d

\n

Okasha had announced a week before the meeting took place on TV that he had invited the ambassador to have dinner with him at his home.

\n

Okasha\u2019s meeting with Koren has been heavily discussed on public affairs shows
column29:
and MENA reports the parliament on Sunday decided to form a special committee to investigate the meeting.

\n
